    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-02-17T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-02-17T12:00:00-05:00" n="412"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d412">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">762.63/441: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-02-17T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >February 17, 1938—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 17—2:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>60. This evening’s press announces that the new Austrian Minister of the Interior
                    Seyss-Inquart arrived in Berlin this morning “for a short visit” and was
                    received by Hitler. It is learned that he also saw Ribbentrop and it is reported
                    that the necessity was impressed upon him in both of these conversations of
                    cleaning up in Austria what was described as “communist elements”. It may be
                    further noteworthy that he spent some time at the offices of the secret
                    police.</p>
                <pb facs="0407" n="399" xml:id="pg_399"/>
                <p>The circumstance of a newly appointed member of the Austrian Cabinet who is known
                    to be pro-German being thus in effect “summoned” to Berlin is construed here as
                    sharply indicative of the nature of the new relationship between Germany and
                    Austria.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
